article.description:
Calbert Cheaney scored a season-high 14
points and Karl Malone added 13 points and eight rebounds as the
Utah Jazz kept Memphis winless on the road by beating the Grizzlies
104-71 Friday night.
article.headline: Hot shooting lifts Jazz to third straight victory
article.linkText: Jazz keep Grizzlies winless on road this season
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Any worries coach Jerry Sloan may have had about the Utah Jazz overlooking the lowly Memphis Grizzlies went away quickly Friday night. Two nights after a convincing win over the Los Angeles Lakers, the Jazz opened with 12-1 run and continued to pull away in a 104-71 victory, Utah's ninth in 10 games. "I don't think we took them for granted,'' said Utah's Matt Harpring, who had 13 points and seven rebounds. "We wanted to come out and jump on them.'' The Jazz did just that and didn't play a starter in the fourth quarter, leaving them well-rested for Sunday's rematch with the Lakers. Calbert Cheaney scored a season-high 14 points and Karl Malone added 13 points and eight rebounds for the Jazz, who climbed four games above .500 for the first this season. Andrei Kirilenko had 15 points and fellow reserve forward Scott Padgett was 6-for-7 from the floor and scored 14 for Utah, which shot 55.6 percent (45-for-81) while winning its third straight. "We don't lose a lot when we come in,'' Padgett said. "We don't have a Karl Malone or a John Stockton down there, but we can hold our own.'' Memphis lost its fifth in a row and fell to 0-10 on the road, remaining the only team in the league without a victory away from home. "We're beyond frustrated. I know I am,'' said Stromile Swift, who tied his season high with 16 points for the Grizzlies. Lorenzen Wright scored 14 and Wesley Person finished with 12. Rookie Drew Gooden sat out the game with a bruised knee and Shane Battier missed the game with a leg infection. "I think we're a deep team. We can go without those guys,'' Swift said. "We just didn't get it done tonight.'' After falling behind by 11 in the first quarter, the Grizzlies never got closer than five points and were outscored by at least six points in every quarter. Memphis shot just 25-for-73 from the floor, had 23 turnovers and was outrebounded 41-35. Memphis coach Hubie Brown said he thanked Sloan after the game. "Jerry was very kind here tonight, because they could have beat us by 50,'' he said. The Jazz closed the second quarter by scoring the final 10 points. John Stockton and Harpring each hit a pair of shots and Jarron Collins went 2-for-2 from the free throw line to give Utah a 51-34 halftime lead. Stockton, who had eight points and seven assists, opened the third quarter with a long jumper, then Malone made it 55-34 with a steal he took all the way in for a dunk. Memphis went without a field goal for nearly 5½ minutes in the third and finished the quarter just 2-for-16 from the floor as the Jazz pulled ahead by as many as 28. Cheaney, who signed with the Jazz as a free agent over the summer, had never scored more than 12 for Utah. Game notes
The game got off to a sloppy start as the Jazz and Grizzlies combined to miss the first eight shots. Cheaney finally broke the scoreless tie on a short hook with 9:31 left in the quarter. ... The Grizzlies went the first 6 minutes, 16 seconds without a field goal. Wright ended the drought with a baseline jumper that cut the Jazz's lead to 13-3. ... Wright was called for a foul on Malone with 4:37 left in the third and got a technical when he continued to complain about the call. Malone made the shot and Utah led 66-41. ... Every Jazz player got in the game and only John Amaechi, who didn't take a shot, failed to score.
